<article>
  <span class="badge badge-warning">PARTIALLY SAFE</span>
  <h2>2. Manual Sanitization Helps (But Isn't Enforced)</h2>

  <div class="csp-indicator csp-off">
    ● Trusted Types: OFF (no CSP on this page)
  </div>

  <p>
    Sanitizing with <a href="https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify" target="_blank">DOMPurify</a>
    before passing to <code>unsafeHTML()</code> prevents the XSS — the dangerous
    attributes are stripped.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>But nothing enforces this.</strong> Trusted Types exists specifically to
    make sanitization <em>mandatory</em>. Without it, any developer — or any transitive
    dependency — can call <code>unsafeHTML(rawString)</code> and skip DOMPurify entirely.
    The next page shows why Trusted Types doesn't currently help here.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">demo-2.js — what you're running</div>
{% highlight "javascript" %}
import { html, render } from 'lit-html';
import { unsafeHTML } from 'lit-html/directives/unsafe-html.js';
import DOMPurify from '/js/dompurify.js';

const userInput = `<img src=x onerror="alert('XSS!')"> Hello!`;
const sanitized = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);
// sanitized = '<img src="x"> Hello!' — onerror stripped

render(
  html`<div>${unsafeHTML(sanitized)}</div>`,
  document.querySelector('#result')
);
{% endhighlight %}
  </div>

  <div class="demo-area">
    <h3>Interactive Demo</h3>
    <button class="run-btn" id="run-btn">Run Demo</button>
    <div class="result-box" id="result">
      <em style="color:#999">Output will appear here after clicking "Run Demo".</em>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    No alert fires — but only because the developer remembered to call
    <code>DOMPurify.sanitize()</code>. The browser has no way to enforce this.
  </p>

